body:
when I use verilator api `contextp->internalsDump();` to print all scopes and variables' name, I found output's escaped identifiers have some difference with "IEEE Standard for SystemVerilog--Unified Hardware Design, Specification, and Verification Language". The minimal exmaple code have shown below, with verilator commit sha 8a4ceb571.

```verilog
module baz (
    input a,
    output b
);
    assign b =! a;
    
endmodule

module foo (
    input a,
    output b
);
    baz inner (
        .a(a),
        .b(b)
    );
endmodule

module \bar (
    input in0,
    output out0
);

    wire \c+b  ;

    foo \first.foo              (
        .a(in0),
        .b(\c+b )
    );

    foo \second.foo (
        .a(\c+b ),
        .b(out0)
    );

    initial begin
        $finish();
    end

endmodule
```
```cpp
#define VM_PREFIX Vour
#define VM_PREFIX_HDR "Vour.h"

#include VM_PREFIX_HDR
#include "verilated.h"
#include "verilated_vpi.h" // Required to get definitions

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
  Verilated::commandArgs(argc, argv);
  const std::unique_ptr<VerilatedContext> contextp{new VerilatedContext};
  const std::unique_ptr<VM_PREFIX> top{new VM_PREFIX{contextp.get(), ""}};

  contextp->internalsDump(); // See scopes to help debug
  while (!contextp->gotFinish()) {
    top->eval();
  }
  return 0;
}
```
```bash
verilator --debug --cc --exe --build --vpi --public-flat-rw our.v main.cc
```

Language specification 5.6.1 section says: **Escaped identifiers shall start with the backslash character (\\) and end with white space (space, tab, newline).** In the following output, however, **verilator append an extra space char for all escaped identifiers.** 

Specifically, with below outputs, I expect module baz's instance's name is `"bar.\first.foo.inner"` instead of `"bar.\first.foo .inner"`, and expect module bar wire variable' name is `"\c+b"` instead of `"\c+b "`. `obj_dir/Vour__Syms.cpp` record all variables and scopes name.

```txt
❯ ./obj_dir/Vour
internalsDump:
  Version: Verilator 5.023 devel
  Argv:
  scopesDump:
    SCOPE 0x558c18314780: TOP
       VAR 0x558c18314d58: in0
       VAR 0x558c18314dd8: out0
    SCOPE 0x558c183147b8: bar
       VAR 0x558c18314e98: \c+b 
       VAR 0x558c18314f18: in0
       VAR 0x558c18314f98: out0
    SCOPE 0x558c183147f0: bar.\first.foo 
       VAR 0x558c18315058: a
       VAR 0x558c183150d8: b
    SCOPE 0x558c18314828: bar.\first.foo .inner
       VAR 0x558c18315198: a
       VAR 0x558c18315218: b
    SCOPE 0x558c18314860: bar.\second.foo 
       VAR 0x558c183152d8: a
       VAR 0x558c18315358: b
    SCOPE 0x558c18314898: bar.\second.foo .inner
       VAR 0x558c18315418: a
       VAR 0x558c18315498: b
```

I would like to kindly inquire whether such behaviors to be in line with fellow developers' expectations?
if yes, I am eager to hear your opinions and suggestions. if no, could you allow me to raise a pull requests (#5033) to fix it ?
Thank you very much for your time and consideration!
